ARRESTS BY NEW JERSEY TROOPERS SHOW ANOTHER DROP IN SEPTEMBER (DW).
Arrests by the New Jersey State Police were down 42 percent in September from the same period last year and the head of the state troopers union said Wednesday that he attributed the decline to low morale and troopers fear of being accused of racial profiling.
The statistics which are published monthly show a continuing trend of fewer arrests since February when Col.
Williams superintendent of the State Police was forced to resign by Gov.
Williams had said in a newspaper interview at the time that certain racial and ethnic groups dominate segments of the illegal drug trade.
In the month after the resignation the number of arrests also fell 42 percent.
Troopers made 1 042 arrests last month 754 fewer than the 1 796 made in September 1998 according to figures released Tuesday.
The number of traffic summonses issued was also down by about 10 percent to 32 567 last month from 36 074 a year ago.
Trooper Edward Lennon president of the State Troopers Fraternal Organization said the decline the largest since March reflected troopers poor morale and fears of being accused of singling out minority drivers.
7 Lennon said that Troopers John Hogan 29 and James Kenna 28 were indicted on charges of attempted murder and assault in the April 1998 shooting of three unarmed men two of them black and one Hispanic on the New Jersey Turnpike.
The incident led to widespread public criticism as well as state and federal investigations of the force.
I think troopers are less likely to take the step further that is required to initiate a patrol related arrest Lennon said.
When they stop a car for speeding they re issued a summons for speeding and the driver s on his way.
There are indicators like a driver s nervousness that might ordinarily prompt troopers to search a car he said but it could be that they are ignoring those indicators.
John Hagerty a spokesman for the State Police would not comment on Lennon s assertions.
Hagerty said the decline could be linked to the reassignment of 40 troopers to flood relief duty last month or to a continuing decline in the overall crime rate.
Let s not forget that in 1998 we recorded a 9 percent drop in crime and the FBI is telling us we re looking at a similar decline in 1999 he said.
With declining crime rates you re going to have fewer arrests.
Hagerty said troopers were also busier aiding drivers last month with 15 127 reports of assistance compared with 14 277 in September 1998.
The State Police began publishing the monthly figures in April at the recommendation of Peter G.
Verniero then the state attorney general to increase accountability and public confidence in the force.
Hagerty said he could not say whether either goal had been achieved.
State Police get letters pro and con on a daily basis he said.
EX POLICE COMMISSIONER RELISHES BEING BACK IN HUNT FOR TERRORISTS.
WASHINGTON Six years after stepping down as New York City s police commissioner Raymond W.
Kelly finds himself playing cop again this time as commissioner of the U.
Customs Service with a mission that includes tracking down terrorists who might try to cross the borders in time for this week s millennium celebrations.
It feels like I never really left the beat said Kelly who ran the New York City Police Department when terrorists bombed the World Trade Center in 1993 the last deadly attack by foreign terrorists on American soil.
In the last few weeks the Customs Service seems to have proved that the potential millennium threat is real.
14 customs inspectors arrested an Algerian man Ahmed Ressam as he crossed from Canada into Washington state.
Prosecutors said his car was packed with a nitroglycerine like chemical and other bomb making components.
he had a reservation at a motel in Seattle near the Space Needle.
Seattle officials later canceled the public celebration there because of security concerns.
And five days after Ressam s arrest customs agents in Vermont detained two people who have since been tied by prosecutors to Algerian militant groups.
Kelly speaks somberly of what the arrests might suggest.
We ve got to be concerned he said his stocky compact frame and thick New York accent bringing Jimmy Cagney to mind.
He recalled rushing to the World Trade Center on Feb.
26 1993 when a bomb unleashed a fireball killing six people and leaving a seven story crater where a parking garage had been.
The thing I remember most vividly he said was looking down and seeing this hole this huge hole.
But every so often the solemnity in Kelly s voice gives way to his obvious excitement at how the Customs Service among the least glamorous of law enforcement agencies has found itself on the front lines of the war against terrorism.
Yes absolutely I feel energized invigorated he said.
He is convinced that the professionalism of his agents in Washington state prevented a terrorist attack.
The arrest prompted President Clinton to announce a heightened state of alert for federal law enforcement agencies.
In the last two weeks Kelly has added 500 inspectors to border stations.
This whirlwind of excitement is a reminder of why he told Clinton last year that he wanted to run the Customs Service.
It was technically a demotion from his last job as the Treasury Department s undersecretary for enforcement a post in which he supervised not only the Customs Service but also the Secret Service and the Bureau of Alcohol Tobacco and Firearms.
It was a step down but it was an inside the beltway step down he said.
Undersecretary was a policy job and that s fine and I enjoyed it.
There were worries earlier this year that Kelly might have to cut short his tenure.
This was a shock to me said Kelly a 58 year old Marine Corps veteran who always prided himself on staying in shape.
He was back at work within days of the surgery and has resumed his daily visits to the gym in his condominium complex spending 40 minutes on a treadmill before hitting the weights.
As New York s police commissioner Kelly had a resume drawn up by central casting.
The youngest of five children he was raised in a building at Columbus Avenue and 91st Street in Manhattan It s now a McDonald s he says with a sigh before moving to Queens as a teen ager.
His father a milkman later worked for the Internal Revenue Service.
His one sister worked in the fashion industry before retiring.
Like his three brothers Kelly joined the Marines.
While working in the stockroom in the baby clothes department at Macy s Kelly saw a recruiting ad for the police.
He registered at the Police Academy graduating first in a class of 1 800.
His tenure as police commissioner was brief only 18 months but Kelly was praised for his performance both for the overall decline in the crime rate and for his sensitivity to racial concerns.
Jimmy Breslin the newspaper columnist described him as a city treasure.
Kelly said he had long wondered what else he might have accomplished had Mayor Rudolph Giuliani not decided shortly after his election in November 1993 to find a new commissioner.
Giuliani had the absolute right to pick his own police commissioner he said.
He still sees plenty of New York where his wife who sells medical equipment lives in their apartment in Battery Park City in Lower Manhattan.
We have a commuting deal and she ll come down to Washington virtually every weekend if I don t go up he said.
NEW ORLEANS (AP) A week after Mayor Marc Morial received a national award for overhauling the city police department and a coinciding drop in crime two teen agers were murdered after leaving a weekend party in an upscale neighborhood.
Four more people have been killed since then the latest victims in a disturbing trend.
There have been 110 murders in New Orleans this year compared with 80 by the same time a year ago.
Selected checks of major cities including Baltimore Boston Dallas Los Angeles New York and Philadelphia found that murders are up over last year.
The increases follow a substantial drop in murder rates across the country during most of the last decade.
In May the FBI said murder and other serious crimes reported to the police dropped for an eighth consecutive year in 1999 by far the longest running crime decline on record.
Murder was down 2 percent in cities over 500 000 and 8 percent overall.
Several leading criminal justice experts agreed that the public should no longer expect to see the same significant drops in the rate of violent crimes that occurred in the 1990s.
But they were unsure whether this year s murder upswing is temporary or whether America s violent crime rate has reached its low point and will now increase.
at some point you can t go any lower said James Alan Fox a criminal justice professor at Northeastern University in Boston.
but the issue of thrill and revenge motivation is still here and remains as American as apple pie and we have not seen an abatement of this type of violence.
Steve Levitt a University of Chicago economics professor who specializes in criminal justice issues actually expects a long term drop in violent crime.
He said unabated prison growth has removed violent offenders from society and is serving as a deterrent.
The murder rate for the first half of the year has dropped in some large cities Denver and Phoenix among them by as much as 28 percent.
Demography is working against us said Fox noting the number of people between 14 and 20 considered crime prone ages is growing.
If we don t pay attention we could see youth violence so bad we ll look back on the 1990s and say Those were the good old days.
When Morial took office in 1994 New Orleans had the nation s worst murder rate.
That has fallen more than 50 percent since then with 162 murders last year.
Conference of Mayors in Seattle on June 10 Morial received the City Livability Award for turning things around.
But now New Orleans is on pace for 230 murders this year the total in 1998.
Police Superintendent Richard Pennington has blamed most of the killing on drug gangs.
The real question may be why the city s 1999 rate was so low according to Al Blumstein a criminal justice professor at Carnegie Mellon University in Pittsburgh.
He said last year s tally was an anomaly.
Unlike Fox Blumstein sees less of a threat posed by the growing population of young people.
The crime rate for that age group has been falling at about 5 percent he said and he expects violent crime rates to level off.
We ve solved the easy stuff now it s going to be a lot harder to go beyond that he said.
None of the experts found evidence that the increase in some city murder rates is due to an economic slowdown.
M economics professor and director of criminal justice at the National Center for Policy Analysis in Dallas instead suggested that recent public embarrassments for police in Los Angeles and New York has left officers more gun shy about the way they treat suspects.
We may be seeing something here in terms of temporary drop in police efficiency because of either morale corruption or scandal he said.
