RATE OF VIOLENT CRIME DROPS 10 PERCENT IN 1999 CONTINUING DOWNWARD TREND.
WASHINGTON The rate of violent crime in the United States continued a downward trend in 1999 with the 10 percent drop last year representing one of the largest decreases in decades the Justice Department said Sunday.
The latest figures released by the department s Bureau of Justice Statistics show a continuation of declines in every major type of personal and property crime between 1993 and 1999.
During this period the rate of violent crimes in general declined 32.
Results of the annual National Crime Victimization Survey begun in 1972 show that property crime rates continue a 25 year downward trend.
Crime rates involving property including burglary and motor vehicle theft dropped 9 percent from 1998 to 1999 decreasing from 217 per 1 000 U.
Americans were more secure in their homes from 1998 to 1999 with the number of completed burglaries dropping from 38.
After a period of slow decline that was interrupted by an increase from 1980 to 1981 the burglary rate fell each year through the rest of the period the Justice Department report said.
The 1999 household burglary rate was about a third that of the adjusted rate of 1973.
Law enforcement officials attribute the continued drop in crime rates to a healthy economy crime prevention programs tougher sentences and more police officers on the street.
